│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The transformation is `sub y, (select c, x, -x)` into `add y, (select c, -x, x)`. This is a specific instance of a more general transformation: `sub y, z` -> `add y, (-z)`. The         │
│ `instcombine` pass likely tries to negate the second operand `z` of the `sub`, and if it can simplify `-z`, it replaces the `sub` with an `add`.                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ In this case, `z` is `select c, x, -x`. Negating this gives `-(select c, x, -x)`. This can be pushed into the select: `select c, -x, -(-x))`, which simplifies to `select c, -x, x`.     │
│ This is exactly what the transformed code does.                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The code for this logic is likely in `InstCombiner::visitSub`. It will try to negate `Op1` of the `sub`. A key function for this is `NegateValue`. I will search for calls to            │
